      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The Post-Sale Review: What Brisbane Sellers Should Do After Settlement
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Once the contract is unconditional, the property has settled, and the funds have cleared, most sellers move on. The handful who do a structured post-sale review walk away with better tax outcomes, sharper insight for the next sale, and a clean record of what actually happened.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The natural reaction once a sale settles is relief and a desire to put the entire campaign down. Sellers have usually spent three to six months preparing, marketing, negotiating, and coordinating around the sale; the day funds clear is, in most cases, the day they would prefer to move on. The handful of sellers who pause for a structured post-sale review in the weeks after settlement consistently end up better positioned for tax season, better organised for any insurance, body corporate, or rates loose ends, and better prepared if a future sale (an investment property, a downsize, an interstate move) is on the horizon. The exercise is not long. A focused two hours in the weeks after settlement covers most of what matters.</p>

      <p>This article walks through what a sensible post-sale review looks like for a Brisbane seller. The aim is to give sellers a checklist they can run through on their own kitchen table, with notes on which items justify a phone call to their accountant, conveyancer, or property manager.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Document the financial outcome cleanly</h2>
      <p>The first task is producing a clean financial summary of the sale. The settlement statement from the conveyancer is the primary document, but it does not on its own tell the full story of the campaign cost or the net cash position. A useful summary captures the contract price, the marketing and styling spend, the agent commission, the conveyancing and legal fees, any pre-sale rectification work (a new hot water system, a pool safety upgrade, a building report addressed before listing), settlement adjustments for rates and water, mortgage discharge fees, and any other transaction costs. The result is a single page that shows what came in, what went out, and what landed in the bank account. This is the document the accountant will want at tax time, and it is the document the seller will want if they ever need to reconstruct the campaign for any reason later.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Capital gains tax: investment property and main residence considerations</h2>
      <p>For an investment property, the post-sale review must include the capital gains tax position. The seller's accountant will need the original purchase price, the purchase costs (stamp duty, legal fees, building and pest), the capital improvement spend over the period of ownership (renovations, additions, structural work, but not basic maintenance), the cost base adjustments for periods of main residence use if applicable, the sale price, the sale costs, and the depreciation that has been claimed across the ownership period (which generally reduces the cost base). The CGT discount for assets held more than 12 months by individuals applies to the calculated gain. The relevant tax year is the year in which the contract was signed, not the year of settlement, which can be relevant for sales that contract in June and settle in July. Sellers should not try to calculate this themselves; the accountant should be briefed with the documentation in the months after settlement so it is ready for the next tax return.</p>

      <p>For a main residence, the CGT main residence exemption typically applies in full, but the seller should still confirm this with their accountant if the property has been used for income production at any time (rented out for a period, claimed home office expenses on a portion of the property, partially let on Airbnb), as a partial main residence exemption may apply. The post-sale review is the right moment to surface any of these complexities to the accountant rather than waiting for the tax return.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance and utility loose ends</h2>
      <p>The administrative loose ends are easy to forget but can produce small refunds or, more commonly, prevent ongoing charges on a property the seller no longer owns. Home and contents insurance should be cancelled effective the day of settlement (usually the insurer will refund the unused premium pro rata). Landlord insurance on an investment property follows the same logic. Electricity, gas, internet, and water account closures should be confirmed with the relevant providers; in most cases the seller has organised these through the move, but missed accounts (a redundant security monitoring contract, a forgotten lawn or pool service, a legacy phone line) sometimes surface in the weeks after settlement. A short walk through bank statements from the prior six months identifies any recurring charges associated with the property that need to be cancelled.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Rates, water, and body corporate adjustments</h2>
      <p>Brisbane City Council rates, Queensland Urban Utilities water charges, and (for unit and townhouse sales) body corporate levies are adjusted at settlement on a pro-rata basis between buyer and seller. These adjustments appear on the settlement statement, but sellers should still verify in the months after settlement that the council and water authority records have been updated to reflect the new owner. Occasionally a final rates notice or water bill is sent to the seller's old address by mistake; the seller should redirect any such correspondence to the buyer's solicitor for handling. For body corporate properties, confirm that the body corporate manager has updated the roll and that no further levies are being directed to the former owner.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mortgage discharge confirmation</h2>
      <p>If the property was mortgaged, the discharge of the mortgage at settlement should produce a discharge confirmation from the lender within a few weeks. Sellers should keep this document with the sale records. If the discharge has not been confirmed within four to six weeks of settlement, a follow-up with the lender is worthwhile; uncleared mortgage notations on title can occasionally cause issues with future credit or property transactions. The conveyancer typically handles this, but sellers should confirm rather than assume.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Funds: where the proceeds go</h2>
      <p>The decision about what to do with the sale proceeds is, for many sellers, the most consequential financial decision tied to the sale. For sellers using the proceeds to settle on a simultaneous purchase, the question largely answers itself; the funds flow through to the next purchase with whatever bridging or offset arrangements have been organised. For sellers who are not buying immediately (downsizers cashing out, investors realising a position, sellers relocating with no immediate purchase), the proceeds typically sit in a bank account or offset facility for some period before deployment. The post-sale review is the right moment to think about what that interim arrangement should be (high-interest savings, offset against an existing loan if applicable, short-term term deposit, or working with a financial adviser on a longer-term strategy). The money sitting idle in a transaction account is the most common avoidable inefficiency in the months after a sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The campaign retrospective: what worked, what did not</h2>
      <p>Beyond the financial and administrative review, the most useful thing sellers can do is a candid retrospective on the campaign itself. What worked, what did not, what they would do differently, what surprised them. This is particularly valuable for sellers who own additional property (an investment property, a future-sale family home, a holiday property) and will likely sell again at some point. The notes do not need to be elaborate. A page of observations, written within a few weeks of settlement while the experience is still fresh, is enough.</p>

      <p>Useful prompts include: which preparation investments produced the strongest visible response from buyers, and which did not move the needle? How did the marketing copy and photography read in hindsight? What did the open homes feel like, and how did the agent run them? How did the negotiation phase unfold, and what would have made it cleaner? Were there any moments in the campaign where decisions were made under time pressure that, with more notice, might have been made differently? What was the actual versus expected timeline from listing to settlement? These observations are useful to the seller themselves for the next time, and they are useful to the agent who ran the campaign, who will generally welcome candid feedback that can be applied to future campaigns.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Address change administration</h2>
      <p>The basic address change administration (Australian Electoral Commission, Australia Post mail redirection, Medicare, ATO, banks, superannuation, insurance, employer, professional bodies, school enrolment, vehicle registration, driver's licence) is a separate exercise from the property review but worth acknowledging in the same window. Many sellers handle this through the moving period; the post-sale review is the moment to confirm nothing has been missed. A quick check of statements and correspondence two months after the move usually surfaces any addresses that have not been updated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Setting up records for the future</h2>
      <p>The final step is filing the records cleanly. A single folder (paper or digital) for the sale that contains the contract, the settlement statement, the marketing invoices, the agent agreement, the conveyancer correspondence, the building and pest reports, the pool safety certificate, the disclosure documentation, the discharge of mortgage, and the financial summary is a small investment that pays off the next time anyone (the seller, the accountant, a future buyer of a related property, a family member dealing with an estate) needs to look back at the transaction. Sellers who have done this once for a previous sale know how useful it is the second time around, and how irritating it is to reconstruct the records years later when something is missing.</p>

